item.description:
arXiv:2606.29292v2 Announce Type: replace 
Abstract: Let $(M,g)$ be a smooth closed Riemannian surface, let $X_N$ be a smooth spectral truncation of the massive Gaussian free field, and set $\Phi_{m,N}=\mathopen{:}X_N^m\mathclose{:}$. For dyadic spectral blocks $\Delta_L,\Delta_Q$, $p\ge2$, and $2\le r<\infty$, we prove \[
  \|\Lambda_g^{-a}\Delta_LM_{\Phi_{m,N}}\Delta_Q\Lambda_g^{-b}
  \|_{L^p(\Omega;\mathfrak S_r)}
  \lesssim
  (p+r)^{m/2}\bigl(\log(e+\max\{L,Q\})\bigr)^{m/2}
  \min\{L,Q\}^{2/r}L^{-a}Q^{-b}, \] uniformly in $N$. If $a,b>0$ and $a+b>2/r$, the corresponding global sandwiched multipliers converge in $L^p(\Omega;\mathfrak S_r)$ and almost surely along dyadic ultraviolet cutoffs. The limit is independent of the smooth ultraviolet profile and of the dyadic spectral resolution, and its matrix coefficients agree with the cutoff-independent distributional Wick power. In particular, any positive two-sided smoothing gives a compact operator-norm limit.
  The probabilistic input is a finite-order Gaussian tensor estimate. If \[
  K\in \mathcal A_1\otimes\cdots\otimes\mathcal A_m
  \otimes\overline{\mathcal C}\otimes\mathcal E \] has finite-dimensional support and $\mathcal F_S(K)$ denotes the oriented flattening associated with $S\subset\{1,\ldots,m\}$, then \[
  \|\mathcal T_K^{(m)}\|_{L^p(\Omega;\mathfrak S_r)}
  \le C_m(p+r)^{m/2}
  \max_{S\subset\{1,\ldots,m\}}\|\mathcal F_S(K)\|_{\mathfrak S_r}. \] For fixed $m$, the joint order in $p$ and $r$ is optimal uniformly over finite-dimensional coefficient models. Gaussian regression transfers the estimate to same-field Wick chaos, and simultaneous completion of all oriented flattenings provides the coefficient space used in the surface construction. On the geometric side, a cut-dependent factorization through $L^2(M)$ yields the factor $\min\{L,Q\}^{2/r}$.
